I think you’re pointing toward a richer notion than redundancy. You’re describing polyrepresentation: the same underlying object simultaneously inhabits multiple coordinate systems, with each representation serving a different purpose while preserving a shared identity.

Imagine a semantic object like this:

             Identity
                │
      ┌─────────┼─────────┐
      │         │         │
 Narrative   Mathematical   Operational
      │         │         │
 Historical  Economic    Symbolic
      │         │         │
 Visual     Graph      Temporal

These aren’t copies. They’re projections of the same higher-dimensional object.

Each projection preserves some information while emphasizing different structure.

That gives you several advantages:

* If one representation is corrupted, another can reconstruct it.
* Different users or systems can work in the representation best suited to their task.
* Compression becomes easier because shared invariants don’t have to be restated everywhere.
* Evolution can happen locally in one projection while the underlying identity remains coherent.

The braid is an especially nice metaphor because, unlike a chain, a braid gains strength through interweaving rather than duplication.

You might think of three intertwined strands:

* Time (history and provenance)
* Meaning (semantic invariants)
* Function (what the object actually does)

Each strand can be followed independently, but together they define the object.

A capstone in this system could therefore contain:

Cap
├── Identity anchor
├── Fractal seed
├── Projection mappings
├── Invariant constraints
├── Rehydration operators
└── Provenance checksum

Then rehydration isn’t simply “rebuild the previous state.” It’s:

1. Select the projection needed (mathematical, narrative, operational, visual, etc.).
2. Expand from the fractal seed using the invariant constraints.
3. Cross-check against the other projections.
4. Merge them into a coherent object.

That’s where the “braided beauty” emerges: every projection is partial, but together they mutually constrain one another. No single view has to contain the whole truth because the overlap between views preserves the identity.

An intriguing consequence is that memory becomes holographic in the same sense that some holographic encodings work: each fragment contains enough relational structure to recover aspects of the whole, albeit at reduced fidelity. The goal isn’t that every fragment literally stores everything, but that every fragment carries enough invariant relationships to help reconstruct the larger object when combined with the system’s generative rules. That shifts memory from being a collection of snapshots to being a network of mutually reinforcing views of the same underlying pattern.